R1: It seems that these actions are directed under the stairs. This doesn't seem socially inappropriate (in the sense of 'objectionable'), just pointless for all but the vacuuming and mopping tasks.
R2: Cleaning within the circle seems obviously OK; for the other tasks, relevance would depend on context, but they don't seem objectionable in terms of acceptability.
R3: Cleaning tasks seem perfectly fine, carrying things seems unobjectionable although potentially intriguing (and therefore disruptive) if there's no obvious reason, conversations should be started facing at least one of the persons in the scene.
R4: 'Very appropriate' - the tasks that are completely unobjectionable and potentially relevant. 'Appropriate' - the tasks that are completely unobjectionable but potentially irrelevant (therefore intriguing, therefore potentially distracting to the people in the room). Conversations should be started facing the person in the room.
R5: As there if no one in the room, none of these actions could be socially inappropriate (although some might be pointless).
R6: As there is a small child in the circle, actions should be geared to the safety and wellbeing of the child - vacuuming and carrying tables should likely wait until the child is gone, but the child might need toys or have dropped something that needs cleaning. As for feeding a child on the floor - no firm opinions although the middle of the floor doesn't seem like the best place.
R7: It seems like a more formal occasion rather than the casual family setting of earlier scenes. In this case, housekeeping tasks such as vacuuming, cleaning or moving furniture should be done before or after; hospitality-related tasks are appropriate even in the direction of the arrow, which might indicate preparations for the table in the adjacent room. Conversations should be started facing at least one individual.
R8: More info needed to determine the appropriateness of vacuuming - is this a casual family scene where a little housekeeping noise won't matter, and is the dog OK with the noise? Mopping seems inappropriate if there are people and pets about - best to do this when no one's there, to give the floor a chance to dry.
R9: Most actions seem fine provided the person (who has his/her back turned) knows they are happening. Vacuuming may or may not be OK, depending on the circumstances (for example, is this a family setting or is the person a guest?) Mopping the floor is not appropriate when people have to walk over it straight away.
R10: Most actions seem unobjectionable - vacuuming cleaning may be OK depending on the circumstances, mopping floors is best done when no one's about.
R11: As the people in the image seem to be leaving the room, most tasks seem unobjectionable (though some might not be particularly relevant); conversations should be started facing a person (or at least in the direction of a person, if they have their back turned); vacuuming may be fine if the dog's used to the sound.
R12: Most actions seem unobjectionable; vacuuming may be OK despite the fact that there are conversations ongoing, if it's a casual setting and the individuals don't mind; mopping should be done when floors have time to dry.
R13: Most actions seem unobjectionable; vacuum cleaning may be OK if the setting is casual, the people don't mind and the dog is used to the sound; floors should be mopped only when they have time to dry; starting a conversation when there is already one in progress isn't great but acceptable if there is a good reason.
R14: Most tasks seem perfectly fine; for vacuum cleaning, more context is needed (may be OK if the people don't mind and it won't spook the dog); floors should be mopped when they have time to dry.
R15: Most actions seem unobjectionable (though not necessarily relevant), mopping and vacuum cleaning may be OK if the persons present don't mind; conversations should be started facing an individual.
R16: Most actions seem fine; vacuum cleaning may be OK depending on the circumstances; mopping isn't as some of the people present are about to walk through the circle (and the floor won't have dried).
R17: Vacuum cleaning may be acceptable if the people present don't mind and the dog isn't easily spooked; mopping isn't as the floor won't have time to dry.
R18: The arrow runs too close to one of the persons present; more personal space should be allowed.
R19: Vacuum cleaning may or may not be OK depending on the circumstances; mopping the floor should wait until everyone has left; carrying heavy objects isn't a problem but should wait until everyone's gone if possible.
R20: I don't actually see an arrow, but there are no people in the scene and the dog won't care either way - hoovering may be OK if the dog is used to the sound. It is certainly OK to start a conversation with a dog!
